The paper discusses randomized incremental algorithms for several problems in computational geometry and graph algorithms, such as Delaunay triangulation, closest pair, and strongly connected components. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also analyzes the dependence structure of these algorithms and presents a framework for analyzing them, which suggests that cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses work-efficient and polylogarithmic-depth parallel algorithms, which suggests that cs.LG (Machine Learning) may also be a relevant sub-category.
